# (3) Remove all accents, and capitalization, from the string “Jóżef Piłsudski Institute of America”
# Modify the program in part (1) to use loop, and regular expression in reading the list, and handle capital, and special character.
print("***** part (3) *****")
a = ["Jóżef Piłsudski Institute of America"]
a[0] = "".join(x for x in unicodedata.normalize("NFKD", a[0]) if not unicodedata.combining(x))
a[0] = a[0].lower()
a[0] = re.sub("[^a-zA-Z]", " ", a[0])
print(a)

# The method is the same as part (2). But in reading the list, using loop, to use regular expression in handling special character.

# (4) Make all but the last 3 letters lower case

# Modify the program in part (1) to make the following replacements: “I used” to “i used” “The Apple” to “The apple”
# using regular expression.
print("***** part (4) *****")
print("I used ipad to read ebook.")
a = "I used ipad to read ebook."
a = re.sub("I used", "i used", a)
a = re.sub("The Apple", "The apple", a)
print(a)

# Regular expression can change word with different case, so easy to implement this program.

# (5) Splitting of email addresses
# Split email address “John.Smith@company.com” into two substrings (“John Smith” and “company.com”).
# Using regular expression, to split email address into two substrings.
print("***** part (5) *****")
a = "John.Smith@company.com"
a = re.split("[@]", a)
a[0] = re.sub("[\\.]", " ", a[0])
a[0] = a[0].title()
print(a)
